<p><br></p><p><br></p><h2>Fragments in Arabic&nbsp;</h2><p><br></p><p>There are 5 Fragments :</p><p><br></p><ul><li><strong>الجار والمجرور</strong></li><li><strong>حرف النّصب واسمها</strong></li><li><strong>الإضافة</strong></li><li><strong>الموصوف والصِّفَة</strong></li><li><strong>اسم الإشارة</strong></li></ul><p><br></p><p><br></p><h1><span style="font-size: 30px;">الموصوف والصِّفَة :&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</h1><p><br></p><p>This fragment has two main components:</p><ul><li><strong>الموصوف</strong>: The main noun (subject) we’re describing.</li><li><strong>الصفة</strong>: The adjective that describes the noun</li></ul><p><br></p><p>Unlike English, where adjectives precede nouns, in Arabic, the adjective follows the noun. Both parts of this fragment must match in all four noun properties.</p><p><br></p><p>Grammatically, a موصوف&nbsp; must match with its&nbsp; صفة&nbsp; in all four properties.</p><p><br></p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt=""></p><p><br></p><p>It’s important to note that when the names of Allah appear in succession, they are not considered&nbsp; Mowsoof Sifah&nbsp;  even though they match in all four grammatical properties (gender, number, case, and definiteness). This is a common occurrence in the Quran and often emphasizes specific divine attributes individually rather than as modifiers of one another.</p><p><strong>Examples:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>العليم الحكيم</strong> (The All-Knowing, The Wise)</li><li><br></li></ul><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><h1><span style="font-size: 16px;"><strong style="font-size: 30px;">The Pointing Fragment (اسم الإشارة)</strong>
</span></h1><p><span style="font-size: 16px;">Comprising two parts:</span></p><p><span style="font-size: 16px;"><br></span></p><ul><li><strong>اسم الإشارة</strong>: The pointing word, such as "this" or "that" in English.</li><li><strong>المشار إليه</strong>: The noun being pointed at.</li></ul><p><br></p><ul><li>Both parts must match in all four properties.</li><li>The noun pointed at must have a definite article (ال).</li><li>No word can come between the pointing word and the noun.</li></ul><p><br></p><p>Below are Ismul Isharah used for pointing at something that is NEAR. MEMORIZE them along with their<br>meaning.</p><table><thead><tr><th><br></th><th><strong>Plural (هٰؤُلاءِ)</strong></th><th><strong>Pair (هٰذانِ)</strong></th><th><strong>Singular (هٰذا)</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Feminine</strong></td><td>هٰؤُلاءِ (these)</td><td>هٰتَان (both of these)</td><td>هٰذِهِ (this)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Masculine</strong></td><td>هٰؤُلاءِ (these)</td><td>هٰذانِ (both of these)</td><td>هٰذا (this)</td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><p>Below are Ismul Isharah used for pointing at something that is FAR. MEMORIZE them along with their<br>meaning.</p><p>&lt;thead dir="rtl"&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th&gt;****&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SINGULAR&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PAIR&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PLURAL&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/thead&gt;&lt;tbody&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Masc.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;ذَٰلِكَ (That)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;ذَانِكَ (Both of those)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;أُولَئِكَ (those)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fem.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;تِلْكَ (That)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;تَانِكَ (Both of those)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;أُولَئِكَ (those)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/tbody&gt;</p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt=""></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><br></p><p><span style="font-size: 16px;"><br></span></p><p><br></p><br>
